# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-secret-manager
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] In computer security, an **access-control list** (**ACL**) is a list of permissions associated with a system resource (object or facility).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] An ACL specifies which users or system processes are granted access to resources, as well as what operations are allowed on given resources.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Each entry in a typical ACL specifies a subject and an operation.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Many kinds of operating systems implement ACLs or have a historical implementation; the first implementation of ACLs was in the filesystem of Multics in 1965.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] A filesystem ACL is a data structure (usually a table) containing entries that specify individual user or group rights to specific system objects such as programs, processes, or files.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] These entries are known as access-control entries (ACEs) in the Microsoft Windows NT, OpenVMS, and Unix-like operating systems such as Linux, macOS, and Solaris.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Each accessible object contains an identifier to its ACL.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] The privileges or permissions determine specific access rights, such as whether a user can read from, write to, or execute an object.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] In some implementations, an ACE can control whether or not a user, or group of users, may alter the ACL on an object.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] One of the first operating systems to provide filesystem ACLs was Multics.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] PRIMOS featured ACLs at least as early as 1984.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] In the 1990s the ACL and role-based access control (RBAC) models were extensively tested and used to administer file permissions.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] POSIX 1003.1e/1003.2c working group made an effort to standardize ACLs, resulting in what is now known as "POSIX.1e ACL" or simply "POSIX ACL".
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] The POSIX.1e/POSIX.2c drafts were withdrawn in 1997 due to participants losing interest for funding the project and turning to more powerful alternatives such as NFSv4 ACLs.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] As of December 2019, no live sources of the draft could be found on the Internet, but it can still be found in the Internet Archive.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Most of the Unix and Unix-like operating systems (e.g.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Linux since 2.5.46 or November 2002, FreeBSD, or Solaris) support POSIX.1e ACLs (not necessarily draft 17).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] ACLs are usually stored in the extended attributes of a file on these systems.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] NFSv4 ACLs are much more powerful than POSIX draft ACLs.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Unlike draft POSIX ACLs, NFSv4 ACLs are defined by a published standard, as part of the Network File System.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] NFSv4 ACLs are supported by many Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Examples include AIX, FreeBSD, Mac OS X beginning with version 10.4 ("Tiger"), or Solaris with ZFS filesystem, support NFSv4 ACLs, which are part of the NFSv4 standard.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] There are two experimental implementations of NFSv4 ACLs for Linux: NFSv4 ACLs support for Ext3 filesystem and the more recent Richacls, which brings NFSv4 ACLs support for Ext4 filesystem.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] As with POSIX ACLs, NFSv4 ACLs are usually stored as extended attributes on Unix-like systems.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] NFSv4 ACLs are organized nearly identically to the Windows NT ACLs used in NTFS.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] NFSv4.1 ACLs are a superset of both NT ACLs and POSIX draft ACLs.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Samba supports saving the NT ACLs of SMB-shared files in many ways, one of which is as NFSv4-encoded ACLs.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Microsoft's Active Directory service implements an LDAP server that stores and disseminates configuration information about users and computers in a domain.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Active Directory extends the LDAP specification by adding the same type of access-control list mechanism as Windows NT uses for the NTFS filesystem.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Windows 2000 then extended the syntax for access-control entries such that they could not only grant or deny access to entire LDAP objects, but also to individual attributes within these objects.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] On some types of proprietary computer hardware (in particular, routers and switches), an access-control list provides rules that are applied to port numbers or IP addresses that are available on a host or other layer 3, each with a list of hosts and/or networks permitted to use the service.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Although it is additionally possible to configure access-control lists based on network domain names, this is a questionable idea because individual TCP, UDP, and ICMP headers do not contain domain names.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Consequently, the device enforcing the access-control list must separately resolve names to numeric addresses.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] This presents an additional attack surface for an attacker who is seeking to compromise security of the system which the access-control list is protecting.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Both individual servers and routers can have network ACLs.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Access-control lists can generally be configured to control both inbound and outbound traffic, and in this context they are similar to firewalls.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Like firewalls, ACLs could be subject to security regulations and standards such as PCI DSS.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] ACL algorithms have been ported to SQL and to relational database systems.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Many "modern" (2000s and 2010s) SQL-based systems, like enterprise resource planning and content management systems, have used ACL models in their administration modules.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] In 2024, schema-indexed ACL models emerged as a lightweight alternative to traditional JSON-based permission storage.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] One notable proposal introduced the idea of storing only the indexes of allowed operations, rather than full permission trees.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] This technique, later formalized as *SCode ACL*, allows compact encoding of access rights (e.g., `"0 2 5"`) based on a predefined flattened schema, making it particularly efficient for use in stateless systems such as JWT tokens or session cookies.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] The approach gained early traction in developer communities for its minimalism and performance, and has since been adopted in both small-scale and production-grade systems.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] The main alternative to the ACL model is the role-based access-control (RBAC) model.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] A "minimal RBAC model", *RBACm*, can be compared with an ACL mechanism, *ACLg*, where only groups are permitted as entries in the ACL.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] Barkley (1997) showed that *RBACm* and *ACLg* are equivalent.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] In modern SQL implementations, ACLs also manage groups and inheritance in a hierarchy of groups.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] So "modern ACLs" can express all that RBAC express and are notably powerful (compared to "old ACLs") in their ability to express access-control policy in terms of the way in which administrators view organizations.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/access-control-list] For data interchange, and for "high-level comparisons", ACL data can be translated to XACML.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] An **audit trail** (also called **audit log**) is a security-relevant chronological record, set of records, and/or destination and source of records that provide documentary evidence of the sequence of activities that have affected at any time a specific operation, procedure, event, or device.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] Audit records typically result from activities such as financial transactions, scientific research and health care data transactions, or communications by individual people, systems, accounts, or other entities.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] The process that creates an audit trail is typically required to always run in a privileged mode, so it can access and supervise all actions from all users; a normal user should not be allowed to stop/change it.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] Furthermore, for the same reason, the trail file or database table with a trail should not be accessible to normal users.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] Another way of handling this issue is through the use of a role-based security model in the software.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] The software can operate with the closed-looped controls, or as a 'closed system', as required by many companies when using audit trail functionality.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] In telecommunications, the term means a record of both completed and attempted accesses and service, or data forming a logical path linking a sequence of events, used to trace the transactions that have affected the contents of a record.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] In information or communications security, information audit means a chronological record of system activities to enable the reconstruction and examination of the sequence of events and/or changes in an event.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] Information put away or transmitted in paired structure that might be depended upon in court.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] An audit trail is a progression of records of computer data about a working framework, an application, or client exercises.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] Computer frameworks may have a few audit trails each gave to a specific sort of action.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] Related to proper apparatuses and systems, audit trails can help with distinguishing security infringement, execution issues and application issues.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] Routine log audits and investigation are valuable for distinguishing security episodes, approach infringement, fake movement, and operational issues soon after they have happened, and for giving information valuable to settling such issues.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] Audit logs can likewise be valuable for performing forensic investigation, supporting the associations inside examinations, setting up baselines, and distinguishing operational patterns and long run issues.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] In nursing research, it refers to the act of maintaining a running log or journal of decisions relating to a research project, thus making clear the steps taken and changes made to the original protocol.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] In accounting, it refers to documentation of detailed transactions supporting summary ledger entries.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] This documentation may be on paper or on electronic records.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] In online proofing, it pertains to the version history of a piece of artwork, design, photograph, video, or web design proof in a project.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] In clinical research, server based systems such as clinical trial management systems (CTMS) require audit trails.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] Anything regulatory or QA/QC related also requires audit trails.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] In pharmaceutical manufacturing, it is a Good Manufacturing Practice regulatory requirement software generate audit trails, but not all software have audit trail functionality built-in.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] The first 'generic' audit trail generating software came out late 2021.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] The software is called Audit Trail Control, capable of fulfilling regulatory requirements for any software used in pharmaceutical manufacturing.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] In voting, a voter-verified paper audit trail is a method of providing feedback to voters using a ballotless voting system.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] In employment and human resources contexts, audit trails provide a documented record of investigative steps taken, including complaint intake, witness interviews, and remedial actions taken, specifically in cases involving allegations of misconduct, discrimination or harassment.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC), employers are required to conduct a "prompt and adequate investigation" and take "appropriate action based on the findings," making a reviewable audit trail central to demonstrating compliance.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] Multiple regulatory frameworks require organizations to maintain audit trails for compliance purposes.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement hardware, software, and procedural mechanisms that record and examine activity in information systems containing electronic protected health information (ePHI).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] These audit controls, specified under the technical safeguards at 45 CFR 164.312(b), must capture information such as user logins, file accesses, and modifications to ePHI.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would require covered entities to review audit logs at least once every 30 days to detect unauthorized access or other security incidents.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] The Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX) requires publicly traded companies to maintain adequate internal controls over financial reporting, which in practice necessitates comprehensive audit trails for financial transactions and system access.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/audit-trail] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 10 mandates that organizations track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data through logging mechanisms.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] A **credential** is a piece of any document that details a qualification, competence, or authority issued to an individual by a third party with a relevant or *de facto* authority or assumed competence to do so.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Examples of credentials include academic diplomas, academic degrees, certifications, security clearances, identification documents, badges, passwords, user names, keys, powers of attorney, and so on.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Sometimes publications, such as scientific papers or books, may be viewed as similar to credentials by some people, especially if the publication was peer reviewed or made in a well-known journal or reputable publisher.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] A person holding a credential is usually given documentation or secret knowledge (*e.g.,* a password or key) as proof of the credential.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Sometimes this proof (or a copy of it) is held by a third, trusted party.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] While in some cases a credential may be as simple as a paper membership card, in other cases, such as diplomas, it involves the presentation of letters directly from the issuer of the credential its faith in the person representing them in a negotiation or meeting.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Counterfeiting of credentials is a constant and serious problem, irrespective of the type of credential.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] A great deal of effort goes into finding methods to reduce or prevent counterfeiting.In general, the greater the perceived value of a credential, the more significant the problem of counterfeiting, and the greater the lengths to which the issuer must go to prevent fraud.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] In diplomacy, credentials, also known as a letter of credence, are documents that ambassadors, diplomatic ministers, plenipotentiaries, and chargés d'affaires provide to the government to which they are accredited, for the purpose, chiefly, of communicating to the latter the envoy's diplomatic rank.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] It also contains a request that full credence be accorded to his official statements.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Until his credentials have been presented and found in proper order, an envoy receives no official recognition.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] The credentials of an ambassador or minister plenipotentiary are signed by the head of state, those of a chargé d'affaires by the foreign minister.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Diplomatic credentials are granted and withdrawn at the pleasure of the issuing authority, based on widely varying criteria.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] A receiving government may reject a diplomat’s credentials by declining to receive them, but in practice this rarely happens.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] In medicine, the process of credentialing is a detailed review of all permissions granted a medical doctor, physician assistant or nurse practitioner at every institution at which he or she has worked in the past, to determine a risk profile for them at a new institution.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] It vets the practitioner for both receiving practice insurance and the ability to bill to insurance for patient care.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] As well, it certifies legal and administrative body requirements, such as the Joint Commission.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Medical practitioners must also have credentials in the form of licenses issued by the government of the jurisdictions in which they practice, which they obtain after suitable education, training, and/or practical experience.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Most medical credentials are granted for a practice specific group.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] They may also be withdrawn in the event of fraud or malpractice by their holders.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Typically they require continuing education validation and renewal to continue practice.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Information systems commonly use credentials to control access to information or other resources.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] The classic combination of a user's account number or name and a secret password is a widely used example of IT credentials.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] An increasing number of information systems use other forms of documentation of credentials, such as biometrics (fingerprints, voice recognition, retinal scans), X.509, public key certificates, and so on.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Credentials in cryptography establish the identity of a party to communication.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Usually they take the form of machine-readable cryptographic keys and/or passwords.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Cryptographic credentials may be self-issued, or issued by a trusted third party; in many cases the only criterion for issuance is unambiguous association of the credential with a specific, real individual or other entity.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Cryptographic credentials are often designed to expire after a certain period, although this is not mandatory.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] An X.509 public key certificate is an example of a cryptographic credential.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Operators of vehicles such as automobiles, boats, and aircraft must have credentials in the form of government-issued licenses in many jurisdictions.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Often the documentation of the license consists of a simple card or certificate that the operator keeps on his person while operating the vehicle, backed up by an archival record of the license at some central location.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Licenses are granted to operators after a period of successful training and/or examination.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] This type of credential often requires certification of good health and may also require psychological evaluations and screening for substance abuse.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Operator licenses often expire periodically and must be renewed at intervals.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Renewal may simply be a formality, or it may require a new round of examinations and training.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] In military and government organizations, and some private organizations, a system of compartmentalizing information exists to prevent the uncontrolled dissemination of information considered to be sensitive or confidential.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Persons with a legitimate need to have access to such information are issued *security clearances,* which can be tracked and verified to ensure that no unauthorized persons gain access to protected information.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Security clearances are among the most carefully guarded credentials.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Often they are granted to individuals only after a lengthy investigation and only after their need to have access to protected information has been adequately justified to the issuing authority.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] The most elaborate security-clearance systems are found in the world's military organizations.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Some credentials of this type are considered so sensitive that their holders are not even permitted to acknowledge that they have them (except to authorized parties).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Documentation of security clearances usually consists of records kept at a secure facility and verifiable on demand from authorized parties.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Security clearances are regularly withdrawn when they are no longer justified, or when the person holding them is determined to be too great a security risk.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] In many democratic nations, press credentials are not required at the national or federal level for any publication of any kind.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] However, individual corporations, and certain government or military entities require press credentials, such as a press pass, as a formal invitation to members of the press which grants them rights to photographs or videos, press conferences, or interviews.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Press credentials indicate that a person has been verified as working for a known publication, and holding a press pass typically allows that person special treatment or access rights.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Some governments impose restrictions on who may work as a journalist, requiring anyone working for the press to carry government-issued credentials.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Restricting press credentials can be problematic because of its limitations on freedom of the press, particularly if government leaders selectively grant, withhold, or withdraw press credentials to disallow critique of government policy.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Any press coverage published under governments that restrict journalism in this way is often treated with skepticism by others, and may not be considered any more truthful or informative than propaganda.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Some trades and professions in some jurisdictions require special credentials of anyone practicing the trade or profession.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] These credentials may or may not be associated with specific competencies or skills.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] In some cases, they exist mainly to control the number of people who are allowed to exercise a trade or profession, in order to control salaries and wages.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Persons acting as merchants, freelancers, etc., may require special credentials in some jurisdictions as well.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Here again, the purpose is mainly to control the number of people working in this way, and sometimes also to track them for tax-reporting or other purposes like people evaluation.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Documentation of academic and professional credentials usually consists of a printed, formal document.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] The issuing institution often maintains a record of the credential as well.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Academic credentials are normally valid for the lifetime of the person to whom they are issued.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Acquisition of these credentials often leads to increased economic mobility and work opportunity, especially for low-income people.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] A general term for academic credentials in the form of a resume is Curriculum vitae, often abbreviated as CV.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] Titles are credentials that identify a person as belonging to a specific group, such as nobility or aristocracy, or a specific command grade in the military, or in other largely symbolic ways.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/credential] They may or may not be associated with specific authority, and they do not usually attest to any specific competence or skill (although they may be associated with other credentials that do).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] In cryptography, a **hybrid cryptosystem** is one which combines the convenience of a public-key cryptosystem with the efficiency of a symmetric-key cryptosystem.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Public-key cryptosystems are convenient in that they do not require the sender and receiver to share a common secret in order to communicate securely.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] However, they often rely on complicated mathematical computations and are thus generally much more inefficient than comparable symmetric-key cryptosystems.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] In many applications, the high cost of encrypting long messages in a public-key cryptosystem can be prohibitive.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] This is addressed by hybrid systems by using a combination of both.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] The hybrid cryptosystem is itself a public-key system, whose public and private keys are the same as in the key encapsulation scheme.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Note that for very long messages the bulk of the work in encryption/decryption is done by the more efficient symmetric-key scheme, while the inefficient public-key scheme is used only to encrypt/decrypt a short key value.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] All practical implementations of public key cryptography today employ a hybrid system.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Examples include the TLS protocol and the SSH protocol, that use a public-key mechanism for key exchange (such as Diffie-Hellman) and a symmetric-key mechanism for data encapsulation (such as AES).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] The OpenPGP file format and the PKCS#7 file format are other examples.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Hybrid Public Key Encryption (HPKE, published as RFC 9180) is a modern standard for generic hybrid encryption.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] HPKE is used within multiple IETF protocols, including Messaging Layer Security (MLS), Oblivious DNS over HTTPS, Oblivious HTTP, Privacy Preserving Measurement, and TLS Encrypted Client Hello.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Envelope encryption is an example of a usage of hybrid cryptosystems in cloud computing.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] In a cloud context, hybrid cryptosystems also enable centralized key management.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Generates a fresh symmetric key for the data encapsulation scheme.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Encrypts the message under the data encapsulation scheme, using the symmetric key just generated.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Encrypts the symmetric key under the key encapsulation scheme, using Alice's public key.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Sends both of these ciphertexts to Alice.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Uses this symmetric key to decrypt the message contained in the data encapsulation segment.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] If both the key encapsulation and data encapsulation schemes in a hybrid cryptosystem are secure against adaptive chosen ciphertext attacks, then the hybrid scheme inherits that property as well.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] However, it is possible to construct a hybrid scheme secure against adaptive chosen ciphertext attacks even if the key encapsulation has a slightly weakened security definition (though the security of the data encapsulation must be slightly stronger).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Envelope encryption is term used for encrypting with a hybrid cryptosystem used by all major cloud service providers, often as part of a centralized key management system in cloud computing.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Envelope encryption gives names to the keys used in hybrid encryption: Data Encryption Keys (abbreviated DEK, and used to encrypt data) and Key Encryption Keys (abbreviated KEK, and used to encrypt the DEKs).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] In a cloud environment, encryption with envelope encryption involves generating a DEK locally, encrypting one's data using the DEK, and then issuing a request to wrap (encrypt) the DEK with a KEK stored in a potentially more secure service.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Then, this wrapped DEK and encrypted message constitute a ciphertext for the scheme.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] To decrypt a ciphertext, the wrapped DEK is unwrapped (decrypted) via a call to a service, and then the unwrapped DEK is used to decrypt the encrypted message.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] In addition to the normal advantages of a hybrid cryptosystem, using asymmetric encryption for the KEK in a cloud context provides easier key management and separation of roles, but can be slower.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] In cloud systems, such as Google Cloud Platform and Amazon Web Services, a key management system (KMS) can be available as a service.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] In some cases, the key management system will store keys in hardware security modules, which are hardware systems that protect keys with hardware features like intrusion resistance.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] This means that KEKs can also be more secure because they are stored on secure specialized hardware.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Envelope encryption makes centralized key management easier because a centralized key management system only needs to store KEKs, which occupy less space, and requests to the KMS only involve sending wrapped and unwrapped DEKs, which use less bandwidth than transmitting entire messages.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] Since one KEK can be used to encrypt many DEKs, this also allows for less storage space to be used in the KMS.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/envelope-encryption] This also allows for centralized auditing and access control at one point of access.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] In cryptography, a **key derivation function** (**KDF**) is a cryptographic algorithm that derives one or more secret keys from a secret value such as a master key, a password, or a passphrase using a pseudorandom function (which typically uses a cryptographic hash function or block cipher).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] KDFs can be used to stretch keys into longer keys or to obtain keys of a required format, such as converting a group element that is the result of a Diffie–Hellman key exchange into a symmetric key for use with AES.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] Keyed cryptographic hash functions are popular examples of pseudorandom functions used for key derivation.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] The first deliberately slow (key stretching) password-based key derivation function was called "crypt" (or "crypt(3)" after its man page), and was invented by Robert Morris in 1978.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] It would encrypt a constant (zero), using the first 8 characters of the user's password as the key, by performing 25 iterations of a modified DES encryption algorithm (in which a 12-bit number read from the real-time computer clock is used to perturb the calculations).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] The resulting 64-bit number is encoded as 11 printable characters and then stored in the Unix password file.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] While it was a great advance at the time, increases in processor speeds since the PDP-11 era have made brute-force attacks against crypt feasible, and advances in storage have rendered the 12-bit salt inadequate.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] The crypt function's design also limits the user password to 8 characters, which limits the keyspace and makes strong passphrases impossible.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] Although high throughput is a desirable property in general-purpose hash functions, the opposite is true in password security applications in which defending against brute-force cracking is a primary concern.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] Various algorithms have been designed specifically for this purpose, including bcrypt, scrypt and, more recently, Lyra2 and Argon2 (the latter being the winner of the Password Hashing Competition).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] The large-scale Ashley Madison data breach in which roughly 36 million passwords hashes were stolen by attackers illustrated the importance of algorithm selection in securing passwords.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) issued a new revision of their digital authentication guidelines, NIST SP 800-63B-3, stating that: "Verifiers SHALL store memorized secrets [i.e. passwords] in a form that is resistant to offline attacks.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] Memorized secrets SHALL be salted and hashed using a suitable one-way key derivation function.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] Key derivation functions take a password, a salt, and a cost factor as inputs then generate a password hash.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] Modern password-based key derivation functions, such as PBKDF2, are based on a recognized cryptographic hash, such as SHA-2, use more salt (at least 64 bits and chosen randomly) and a high iteration count.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] NIST recommends a minimum iteration count of 10,000.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] The original use for a KDF is key derivation, the generation of keys from secret passwords or passphrases.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] Key derivation functions are also used in applications to derive keys from secret passwords or passphrases, which typically do not have the desired properties to be used directly as cryptographic keys.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] In such applications, it is generally recommended that the key derivation function be made deliberately slow so as to frustrate brute-force attack or dictionary attack on the password or passphrase input value.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] Such use may be expressed as DK = KDF(key, salt, iterations), where DK is the derived key, KDF is the key derivation function, key is the original key or password, salt is a random number which acts as cryptographic salt, and iterations refers to the number of iterations of a sub-function.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] The derived key is used instead of the original key or password as the key to the system.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] The values of the salt and the number of iterations (if it is not fixed) are stored with the hashed password or sent as cleartext (unencrypted) with an encrypted message.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] The difficulty of a brute force attack is increased with the number of iterations.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] A practical limit on the iteration count is the unwillingness of users to tolerate a perceptible delay in logging into a computer or seeing a decrypted message.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] The use of salt prevents the attackers from precomputing a dictionary of derived keys.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] An alternative approach, called **key strengthening**, extends the key with a random salt, but then (unlike in key stretching) securely deletes the salt.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] This forces both the attacker and legitimate users to perform a brute-force search for the salt value.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] Although the paper that introduced key stretching referred to this earlier technique and intentionally chose a different name, the term "key strengthening" is now often (arguably incorrectly) used to refer to key stretching.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] Despite their original use for key derivation, KDFs are possibly better known for their use in **password hashing** (password verification by hash comparison), as used by the passwd file or shadow password file.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] Password hash functions should be relatively expensive to calculate in case of brute-force attacks, and KDFs are designed with this characteristic built in.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] The non-secret parameters are called "salt" in this context.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] In 2013 a Password Hashing Competition was announced to choose a new, standard algorithm for password hashing.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] On 20 July 2015 the competition ended and Argon2 was announced as the final winner.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-derivation-function] Four other algorithms received special recognition: Catena, Lyra2, Makwa and yescrypt.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:gcp-secret-manager/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
